g insulin x1 ordering...')\\n# The parameter parsing: headers have non-numeric labels, so sequential 1,2,3\\n# After normalization: (1-1)/(3-1)=0, (2-1)/(3-1)=0.5, (3-1)/(3-1)=1.0\\n# But which curve is fastest? Curve 2 (0.1% seeds) > Curve 1 (0.05% seeds) > Curve 3 (no seeds)\\n# Header order: 0.05% seeds, 0.1% seeds, no seeds\\n# So: x1=0 -> 0.05% seeds (medium), x1=0.5 -> 0.1% seeds (fastest), x1=1.0 -> no seeds (slowest!)\\n# This is INVERTED - the x1=1 curve is the SLOWEST!\\n# Linear (1+c2*x1) with c2>0 makes x1=1 fastest - WRONG\\n# Linear with c2<0: (1+c2*1) could be small, but (1+c2*0.5) could be negative!\\n# Exp with c2<0: exp(c2*1) < exp(c2*0) - can handle inverted ordering safely\\n\\nprint('If no-seeds is x1=1.0 (slowest), need c2 < 0')\\nprint('Linear: (1 + c2*1) with c2=-0.9 -> 0.1 (10x slower at x1=1)')\\nprint('  But (1 + c2*0.5) = 0.55 - OK')\\nprint('  And (1 + c2*0) = 1.0 - OK')\\nprint('Exp: exp(c2*1) with c2=-2.3 -> 0.1 (10x slower at x1=1)')\\nprint('  exp(c2*0.5) = 0.316')\\nprint('  exp(c2*0) = 1.0')\\nprint('Both work for moderate range, but exp is more stable for large ranges')\\n\\\"\\n\"}"
